Merging is the process of combining changes from one branch into another branch.
Branching is the process of creating a separate copy of the project to work on changes independently.

Commands for branching
git branch	Lists all branches in the repository.
git branch branch-name	Creates a new branch with the given name.
git checkout branch-name	Switches to the specified branch.
git checkout -b branch-name	Creates and switches to a new branch in one step.
git branch -d branch-name	Deletes a branch after it has been merged.
git branch -D branch-name	Force deletes a branch even if it is not merged.
git branch -m new-name	Renames the current branch.

Commands for Merging
git merge branch-name	        Merges the specified branch into the current branch.
git merge --no-ff branch-name	Merges while keeping full branch history.
git merge --abort	            Cancels a merge process if a conflict occurs.